Boil a large #pot of salted water for the @egg noodles{150%grams}.

When the water is boiling, add the noodles and cook until softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve and return to the pot with a splash of @oil{to taste}.

Toss to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, drain the @tofu{280%grams} and chop into 2cm cubes. Pat dry with #kitchen paper.

Toss with a drizzle of oil, half the @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and @pepper{to taste}.

Place a #pan over high heat with a good glug of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, fry the tofu until slightly crispy, ~{6-8%minutes}. Shift frequently to ensure it doesn't burn.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Transfer to a #bowl and cover to keep warm.

Meanwhile, trim the @carrot{1%unit}, quarter lengthways and chop widthways into small pieces (no need to peel).

Halve the @bell pepper{1%unit} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 2cm chunks.

Quarter the @lime{1%unit}.

Return the pan to high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste} (if required).

Add the carrot, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} and fry until tender, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Lower the heat to medium-high and add the pepper. Fry for another ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add the remaining @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} and fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Next add the @peanut butter{1%sachet}, @coconut milk{1%pack}, and @water{150%ml} to the pan. Stir well to combine and bring to the boil.

Remove the pan from the heat and add @sugar{1/4%tsp}, the juice of two lime wedges and the @ketjap manis{1%sachet}.

Taste and season with sugar, salt and pepper. Add a splash of water if the sauce is too thick.

Add the sweet chilli sauce{@sweet chilli sauce{2%sachets}}, drained noodles and tofu to the pan and mix until everything is coated and warmed through, ~{1%minute}.

Share the noodles between plates.

Top with remaining lime wedges.

Finish with a squeeze of lime juice and a drizzle of sweet chilli sauce.